    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT239-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">ciṟaippuṟam. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Hedge. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT239">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> toṭinekiḻn taṉavē tōḷcā yiṉavē</l>
          <l> viṭunā ṇuṇṭō tōḻi viṭarmukaic</l>
          <l> cilampuṭaṉ kamaḻu malaṅkukulaik kānta</l>
          <l> ṇaṟuntā tūtuṅ kuṟuñciṟait tumpi</l>
          <l> pāmpumiḻ maṇiyiṟ ṟōṉṟu</l>
          <l> muntūḻ vēliya malaikiḻa vōṟkē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>The bracelets have become loose, the shoulders are emaciated</l>
          <l>for the master of the mountain with bamboo hedges,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where appears like a jewel <note place="foot">This gem in possession of a
            snake is a topos encountered occasionally − cf. NA 255, AN 192, 372.</note> spit up by a
            snake</l>
          <l rend="indent">the short-winged bee, filling itself up with fragrant pollen</l>
          <l rend="indent2">from the Malabar lily in swaying bunches, all fragrant, <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uṭaṉ kamaḻum</term>: it seems best to take uṭaṉ here
            not as a case marker for cilampu, but, with Cām. (thus also T.V.G.), for a modificator
            of kamaḻum, that is, literally: "smelling together".</note></l>
          <l rend="indent3">on the mountainside with clefts [and] caves.</l>
          <l>Is there [still any] shame to let go of, friend?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
